  <h3 class="glowGlobal">Shred Fundamentals</h3>
  <p>I have broken down my approach to playing lead guitar into two basic categories. The first one contains the scales, modes and arpeggios essential to solo playing and the second one is the patterns and sequences to apply to these scales, modes and arpeggios. If you learn everything in category one and apply the patterns from the second category to them, you can have nearly endless licks at your disposal. More importantly, if you adopt this way of thinking about your playing, you can create unlimited new licks of your own. Let’s get started with the first category!</p>
  <h3 class="glowGlobal">SECTION 1: Scales, Modes and Arpeggios</h3>
  <p>First, we will begin by learning the seven church modes in the key of G Major. Please refer to my blog post on Music Theory Fundamentals to learn about what the modes are and where they come from. All seven modes contain the same seven pitches and pattern of intervals. What makes them different is the note they start and end with. There are seven different pitches, so there are seven different possible places to start…giving us seven different but very related “modes”. These modes define and outline the key (in this case G Major).</p>
  <h3 class="glowGlobal">Church Modes</h3>
  <div id="modesList">
    <ul>
      <li>I -Ionian (Major Scale) / G Major</li>
      <li>ii -Dorian / A minor</li>
      <li>iii -Phrygian / B minor</li>
      <li>IV -Lydian / C Major</li>
      <li>V -Mixolydian / D Major</li>
      <li>vi -Aeolian (Natural Minor Scale) / E minor</li>
      <li>viiº  -Locrian / F# diminished</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
  <br>
  <p>Also, by taking the first, third and fifth notes of these modes, we get their corresponding chords. Those are written next to the mode names above as well as a Roman numeral number that indicates wether each one is major, minor or diminished. Major is uppercase, minor is lowercase and diminished is also lowercase followed by a º symbol. Later, we will also see Augmented chords which are uppercase followed by a + symbol.
    Next, we will put the modes into categories to give them more relative meaning.
    Major Modes – Ionian, Lydian, Mixolydian
    Minor Modes – Dorian, Phrygian, Aeolian
    Diminished Mode – Locrian
    If we now take these modes out of key and play them all starting on the same note, we can see how they are similar and different from each other and allowing us to further understand their characteristics and give them more of their own musical identities.
    Now, we will take these modes and raise all occurrences of D to D#. This is the seventh interval of the Aeolian mode. When we do this, we alter the Aeolian mode to what is called “Harmonic Minor”. But, we must also move the D notes up a half step in all occurrences through all of the modes. This will create a new key and different sounding altered modes and chords.
    Minor Pentatonic Scales
    Like the church modes, the minor pentatonic scale also has its own modes. Five notes in the scale, five different starting points.
    It’s also important to note that the minor pentatonic scale is directly related to the Aeolian Mode. In fact, it is the Aeolian mode minus its second and sixth intervals.
    After we get these all down, let’s add the sharp fourth interval to the scale. This is often  referred to as the “blue note” and changes the scale to a 6 note scale or “hexatonic” scale and introduces the sound and scale we call “The Blues Scale”. Another change we can make is to substitute the minor third interval for a major third and then return to the minor third. This is something found often in blues music and will have a very recognizable sound to many.</p>
