  <p>Hello, and welcome to my first guitar lick lesson on my website! This is a quick and fun one mainly playing a triplet pattern in A Harmonic Minor up the neck. I do throw in some odd passing tones for color but that’s what makes it fun! ;). Hopefully you will find this inspiring and it’ll help you to come up with your own cool licks! Remember to check back here often as I plan on challenging myself to come up with these lessons often! Check out the accompanying video to hear it in action! If you enjoy these and would like to show some support and help me to keep them coming, there’s a little virtual tip jar in the form of a coffee cup in the corner!</p>

  <p>As I mentioned above, this passage is primarily in A Harmonic Minor. I played the lick on my guitar tuned one full step down to D Standard which is what I use in GSO. It is, low to high, the notes DGCFAD. It’s the same as E Standard guitar tuning with each string tuned down one whole step (or two semi-tones). I am going to refer to the guitar positions as if I am tuned to standard tuning just to make it easier for navigating to the correct positions on the neck.
    First of all, I’d like to explain what Harmonic minor is to give all of this some meaning! Harmonic minor is a scale or series of intervals that has a very cool and particular sound and vibe. It’s often called an Exotic or Eastern sounding scale because of its raised 7th interval. The scale comes from the Aeolian mode (please refer to the Blog section of my site to review the modes at this point if needed) and is altered by just one note…the aforementioned raised 7th degree. If we compare the Aeolian mode (aka Natural Minor) to the Ionian mode (Major Scale), aside from the obvious character defining placement of the 3rd (Major in Ionian and minor in Aeolian), there is a similar difference in the 7ths. The Ionian mode has a Major 7th degree which sits naturally one-half step below the tonic. This creates a very pleasing and final sounding resolution when moving from the 7th into the tonic of the next octave. But when we look at Aeolian, we have a minor 7th interval which sits one whole step below the tonic. This does not naturally have the same kind of pleasing resolution that we found in the major scale. Since in music, we often write songs and consider both the Ionian and Aeolian modes as home, wouldn’t it be nice if they both could have that nice half-step resolution into the next octave? Apparently, someone long ago thought just that and altered the Aeolian mode to have this desirable feature by moving this 7th interval up one-half step. By doing this though, you are not only shrinking the distance between the 7th and the tonic, you are also creating a bigger distance on the other side of the 7th down to the 6th. Before the move, there was a full step between the two and now there is a step and a half! This larger interval is not found in any of the original church modes and really introduces a new sound and feeling we had not heard before in a scale! Let me illustrate these differences visually below.

    A (Natural Minor) Aeolian: A--B-C--D--E-F--G--A
    
    This is the intervallic step sequence of: whole, half, whole, whole, half, whole, whole.
    
    A Harmonic Minor: A--B-C--D--E-F-–-G#-A
    
    This is the intervallic step sequence of: whole, half, whole, whole, half, step and a half, half.
    
    Go ahead and try it out on the guitar and listen to the difference!</p>

